post_text: At 5 pm today, Tuesday, June 16, Florida UFSD will begin canvassing the school budget votes cast by residents via absentee ballot. The annual school budget vote is an official public meeting. To afford public access in the midst of social-distancing mandates, the district will livestream the process. The ballot count will be conducted by election inspectors appointed by the Board of Education. This is an opportunity to expose your young children to some of the workings of our democracy. You can watch here, beginning at 5 pm: https://youtu.be/YgRtBis_V44

post_text: SS Seward invites the entire Florida community to join in the celebration of our Class of 2020! A poster-size likeness of each and every single one of our graduating students is now on view on Main Street. Salute them with a honk, or stop by! Many thanks to our PTSA and district volunteers who worked together to honor the high school careers of our students with this beautiful display.

UPDATE: MAIL-IN DEADLINE EXTENDED TO JUNE 16 BY EXECUTIVE ORDER ISSUED JUNE 7!
VOTERS: By now you should have received your absentee ballot in the mail, as well as the district's 2020-21 budget brochure. Voting by absentee ballot is simple, convenient, and equally private. In addition to the mail-in option, you can also drop off your ballot at the district office, Mon-Fri, 9 am-1 pm through June 8. Whether you mail it or drop it off, your ballot must be received by 5 pm on June 9 to be counted. Have questions about voting by absentee ballot, go to https://www.floridaufsd.org/school-budget-vote-by-absentee-ballot-qa-and-how-to-video/

shared_text:
Florida Union Free School District added 124 new photos.
June 2 at 2:52 PM ¬∑

They spent the last 6 years learning about art, discovering their own creative talents and finding inspiration in Mr. Camia's art room. Social distancing wasn't going to keep them from sharing their artwork with the school community they love. Instead, they are making history with Golden Hill's First Virtual Student Art Show, EVER! The "hands" project, inspired by a children's book, was a cross-subject collaboration with ELA teacher Mrs. Meehan. The objects on their hands represent their past, present and future. The pointillism paintings were done using Q-tips and tiny dots of paint on canvas. Enjoy, like and comment!!

2020-21 SCHOOL BUDGET VOTE & BOARD ELECTION: Make sure your vote counts! Hand-delivered ballots must be received by the school district by 5 p.m. on Tuesday, June 9. Mailed ballots must be received by 5 p.m. on June 16 (the mail-in deadline extension reflects an executive order by Gov. Cuomo issued June 7). To be counted, your ballot must be signed. For more information about absentee ballots, go to the district's budget page: https://www.floridaufsd.org/board-of-education/budget-taxes/
If you still have a question, contact the District Clerk at (845) 651-3095.

post_text: Today, NATIONAL SCHOOL NURSE DAY, we want to express our deepest appreciation to our beloved school nurses, Marlene Lysack at Golden Hill, and Eileen Smyth at S.S. Seward. Our nurses lead the way in promoting the health and wellness of our students, and are always there in times of crisis. On a daily basis, they support our educators and administrators by ensuring that students are safe, healthy & ready to learn. Let them know they are valued and appreciated!

post_text: Throughout this time of social distancing and remote learning, parents/guardians and teachers are connecting in unforeseen ways that go beyond technology. As they rely on each other to ensure continuity of learning, there is a growing understanding of the role we all play as partners in education. As we celebrate National Teacher Appreciation Week, we invite you to reflect and share one thing you've recently learned--and appreciate--about the work our teachers do every day.

post_text: As per Governor Andrew Cuomo's announcement today, May 1, all K-12 schools statewide will remain closed and continue to provide distance learning, meal delivery and childcare services for the remainder of the school year. We are all disappointed, especially for our graduating students, but we are determined to continue learning and collaborating for the strongest possible end to the school year. Our new motto is, "Learning apart, together at heart!" Keep checking https://www.floridaufsd.org/ and cheer each other on, right here! More to come on year end activities.

post_text: CONGRATULATIONS to Alexa Roach, named as one of The Times Herald Record V845 girls' basketball all-stars, 2nd team! Roach, Seward's #13 senior forward, scored 548 points this season, averaging 24.9 points per game. She collected 228 rebounds at a clip of 10.2 per contest; delivered 58 3-pointers, with a third of her attempts made from outside the perimeter. She was a 79.6 percent free-throw shooter. Go Alexa! Go Spartans!

post_text: On Monday, April 6, NYS Gov. Cuomo announced that schools will now be closed through April 29. As part of the district's actions to provide continuity of learning, meal distribution and other supports for students, families and staff, Florida schools are partnering with the YMCA to offer no-cost child care services for school-aged children of essential workers, at Golden Hill Elementary. For complete information, and continued updates, go https://www.floridaufsd.org/novel-coronavirus-covid-19-information-and-resources-for-families/

post_text: When today‚Äôs students dream of travel destinations, Mars is likely to make the list. So when Mr. Pekny challenged his principles of engineering students to design Martian landing vehicles for their egg-stronauts it sounded like a practical idea! The Red Planet's thinner atmosphere prevented them from using parachutes or any wind-resistant components, and not all egg-stronauts survived the hard landing, but it was only a test. (Photos by Francesca Gallardo)

post_text: ‚ÄúWhat makes you feel cranky or upset?‚Äù a presenter with BeetleDoo Kids asked Golden Hill students during a recent, interactive performance teaching social-emotional skills. As adults, we expect to face daily stressors, but young children are just beginning to experience them. To help kids work through stressful feelings and still have positive/productive experiences at school and at home, Golden Hill hosted a series of emotional-awareness assemblies for grades K-2. Using playful singalongs, animation, puppets and games, BeelteDoo helps kids connect with themselves and the world around them through the practice of mindfulness. Read the full story: https://www.floridaufsd.org/social-emotional-skills-made-fun-and-easy-for-grades-k-2/

post_text: Mrs. Duquette's Studio in Art students are drawing their own likeness, one small frame at a time. A.k.a., grid drawing, it's an ancient method used to scale some of the world's most massive artworks, e.g., Michelangelo's Sistine Chapel. The technique helps students draw more accurately by processing and reproducing the visual information contained in each individual square, without feeling overwhelmed by the image‚Äôs overall complexity. Read the full story on our website.

post_text:
Here's a sneak peek of the Golden Hill Elementary artwork that will be displayed thoughout the Village of Florida as a tribute to William Henry Seward.
Each May, the Florida Historical Society commemorates the life (and birthday!) of one the nation's influential figures.
Seward was a U.S. Senator, Governor of New York, and Secretary of State under Abraham Lincoln and Andrew Johnson. And he also got the U.S. a great deal on Alaska!

post_text: Super Spartan donates to the Florida Community Food Pantry. We are THANKFUL to you, Ms. Scheuermann!
shared_text:
Florida Community Food Pantry
March 27, 2019 at 7:59 PM ¬∑

Some surprises leaves one grasping for words. Elizabeth Scheuermann's surprise gift to the pantry tonight is one of those moments. Elizabeth participated in TREPS and made custom signs through her business "Savage Signs".

Tonight she gifted the pantry with her entire earnings....$560!!!!!!!! In addition, she presented us with a beautiful personalized sign. We had the perfect spot for it. Forever we will be reminded of her remarkable act of kindness. What a beautiful heart this young lady has!!! Thank you!!!!!

This is Spartan Nation. Florida, NY. We learn here. We don't carry a badge (yet) but we are studying the science of a crime scene.
Students in our SUPA Forensics class recently tested the chemiluminescence reaction of luminol, which glows in the presence of the iron found in blood. And that's just the facts, ma'am.
